  <content>
    <title>Diary Study Execution and Analysis</title>

    <summary>The operational and analytical phase of a running diary study: monitoring participant compliance, detecting low-quality entries, managing drop-off, coding entries against a fixed codebook, computing temporal patterns, and synthesizing findings into a structured report. Lock the codebook before coding begins; adding themes mid-study invalidates cross-participant comparison.</summary>

    <why>
      <p>Diary data is messy by nature: photos, voice notes, free text, sparse entries, copy-paste repetition, emotional venting. Without systematic quality monitoring and a coded pipeline, the expensive longitudinal data collapses into anecdote. Rolling synthesis from day 3 onward (not batch at end) allows follow-up probes while participants are still active.</p>
    </why>

    <when-to-use>
      <list>
        <item>Multi-day diary study is already running and entries (text, photo, voice) are flowing into a single store.</item>
        <item>Cross-participant thematic and temporal coding of more than 50 entries with quote extraction and timeline charts.</item>
        <item>Mid-study quality monitoring: flag low-engagement participants, generic copy-paste entries, missed days.</item>
        <item>Producing the final report from already-coded data.</item>
      </list>
    </when-to-use>

    <when-not-to-use>
      <list>
        <item>Recruitment, screening, or onboarding calls — these require human trust and cannot be delegated to agents.</item>
        <item>Real-time participant chat or probing follow-up DMs while study is live (PII handling, emotional sensitivity).</item>
        <item>Studies where entries are voice-only without transcription pipeline or photos without vision/OCR — no usable text signal.</item>
        <item>Fewer than 5 participants — a human reads everything end-to-end faster than setting up the pipeline.</item>
      </list>
    </when-not-to-use>

    <section name="monitoring">
      <p>Monitor compliance daily and flag participants below 60% completion by day 4. Do not wait until study end to detect dropout. Early dropout is recoverable with a human check-in call. Late detection produces data gaps that make cross-participant comparison unreliable.</p>
      <list>
        <item>Check completion rates daily per participant.</item>
        <item>Send reminders at the scheduled cadence — switch from automated nudges to a single human-style DM after two missed days.</item>
        <item>Monitor data quality: look for generic entries, copy-paste repetition, off-topic content.</item>
      </list>
      <reference path="templates/qa-monitor.sh">Bash script flagging low-completion participants and suspected copy-paste entries.</reference>
    </section>

    <section name="entry-quality-checks">
      <p>Compute text similarity across a participant's entries. Flag entries with cosine similarity above 0.9 as suspected copy-paste before including them in analysis. Copy-paste entries inflate frequency counts for the copied text and suppress the genuine signal from days the participant did not engage. Counting them as real entries poisons temporal pattern analysis.</p>
      <list>
        <item>Generic entries (same text, low detail): prompt participant for specifics in a follow-up message.</item>
        <item>Missed days (gap in submissions): send gentle reminder within 24 hours.</item>
        <item>Copy-paste entries (identical across days): schedule a recovery check-in call.</item>
        <item>Off-topic content: clarify study scope — never silently discard without documenting.</item>
      </list>
    </section>

    <section name="validity-threats">
      <rule>
        <statement>Mitigate self-report bias by using signal-contingent prompts and keeping study duration under 21 days. Acknowledge remaining bias explicitly in the final report.</statement>
        <rationale>Social desirability, memory reconstruction, observation effect, and fatigue all systematically distort self-report data. Transparency about remaining bias prevents stakeholders from over-interpreting findings.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <list>
        <item>Social desirability: participants report what seems "right", not what actually happened.</item>
        <item>Memory reconstruction: entries written hours after events reconstruct rather than recall.</item>
        <item>Observation effect: behavior changes when participants know they are being studied.</item>
        <item>Fatigue effects: entry quality and detail decline over the second half of long studies.</item>
      </list>
    </section>

    <section name="engagement-and-drop-off">
      <rule>
        <statement>Pay incentives in tranches (30% at week 1 completion, 70% at study end). Pre-paid full incentives correlate with mid-study dropout.</statement>
        <rationale>Tranche payment keeps commitment active through the critical second week when fatigue peaks. Pre-payment removes the ongoing motivation to continue.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <rule>
        <statement>Send a personal check-in call (15 minutes) at the midpoint of the study. This single intervention lifts completion rates measurably.</statement>
        <rationale>Check-in calls rebuild commitment and catch confusion about entry expectations before the participant fully disengages. Automated reminders alone cannot substitute for this human contact.</rationale>
      </rule>
    </section>

    <section name="codebook">
      <rule>
        <statement>Lock the codebook before coding begins. Adding a theme mid-study invalidates earlier passes — re-run the coder agent on the full dataset if the codebook changes.</statement>
        <rationale>Cross-participant frequency counts are only valid when all entries are coded against the same taxonomy. Mid-study codebook additions create systematic gaps in earlier participant data.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <rule>
        <statement>Keep the codebook to 6-12 themes with explicit definitions. Force the coder to return an empty themes array when no code fits rather than inventing a match.</statement>
        <rationale>Larger codebooks produce lower inter-rater reliability. Agents over-classify when forced to assign a code to every entry — a NULL result is real data about entry quality or scope drift.</rationale>
      </rule>
    </section>

    <section name="coding-pass-rules">
      <rule>
        <statement>Code each entry independently without exposing the coder to other participants' entries or prior hypotheses. Run two independent passes on a 10% sample and compute Cohen's kappa. Below 0.6 means the codebook is ambiguous.</statement>
        <rationale>Hypothesis exposure causes confirmation bias that amplifies in agents when the prompt mentions a research question upfront. Kappa below 0.6 indicates the codebook has ambiguous boundaries that will produce unreliable frequency counts.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <rule>
        <statement>Require the coder to cite verbatim text fragments per theme. This lets the synthesizer pull real quotes without re-reading raw entries.</statement>
        <rationale>Paraphrased quotes introduce researcher interpretation into participant voice. Verbatim extraction is the only defensible standard for evidence in a research report.</rationale>
      </rule>
    </section>

    <section name="temporal-analysis">
      <rule>
        <statement>Tag every entry with its study day and prompt type (signal-contingent vs event-contingent vs end-of-day). Compute per-day sentiment timelines with date metadata — not free-text dates from entry content.</statement>
        <rationale>Temporal patterns (e.g., day 3-5 frustration spike) are invisible to a single-pass summarizer. Free-text date parsing is unreliable; structured metadata is required for timeline visualizations.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <list>
        <item>Temporal patterns: behavior changes over time, learning curves, habit formation points, drop-off triggers.</item>
        <item>Contextual patterns: location-based behaviors, device preferences, time-of-day patterns.</item>
        <item>Thematic patterns: recurring problems, common delighters, unmet needs, workarounds.</item>
      </list>
    </section>

    <section name="report-structure">
      <rule>
        <statement>Run rolling synthesis from day 3, not batch at study end. Late synthesis loses the chance to add follow-up probes while participants are still active.</statement>
        <rationale>Diary entries become the interview script for exit interviews. Themes identified early can generate targeted follow-up questions. Waiting until end produces a comprehensive analysis of an unprobed dataset.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <reference path="templates/synthesis.md">Analysis synthesis skeleton: participation summary, theme blocks with verbatim quotes, temporal patterns, recommendations.</reference>
      <list>
        <item>Executive summary: key findings (3-5 bullets) and top recommendations.</item>
        <item>Method: study design, participant profile, data collection details.</item>
        <item>Findings: themes with evidence, temporal patterns, context patterns, quantitative summary.</item>
        <item>Recommendations: prioritized actions with evidence and success metrics.</item>
        <item>Appendix: full data, additional quotes, methodology details including bias mitigations.</item>
      </list>
    </section>

    <section name="antipatterns-cherry-picking">
      <antipattern>
        <description>Reporting only positive or interesting findings and omitting negative or null results.</description>
        <reason>Selective reporting produces recommendations that solve interesting problems rather than the most frequent or severe ones. Stakeholders make investment decisions on incomplete evidence and are surprised when predicted improvements do not materialize.</reason>
      </antipattern>
      <rule>
        <statement>Report all findings, including null results and findings that contradict the research hypothesis. Document the evidence base for each finding, not just the finding itself.</statement>
        <rationale>The credibility of diary study research depends on the complete evidence record. A researcher who reports only supportive evidence is doing advocacy, not research.</rationale>
      </rule>
    </section>

    <section name="antipatterns-ignoring-outliers">
      <antipattern>
        <description>Excluding extreme or unusual participant experiences because they are "edge cases" without examining what causes them.</description>
        <reason>Outlier participants often reveal failure modes that affect a larger segment of users who simply do not voice their experience. A participant who fails dramatically often shows you what will happen at scale when less vocal users encounter the same condition.</reason>
      </antipattern>
    </section>

    <section name="antipatterns-losing-context">
      <antipattern>
        <description>Analyzing entries as isolated data points without tracking the individual participant's journey over time.</description>
        <reason>A single negative entry from a participant who was positive on days 1-6 carries completely different meaning than the same entry from a participant who was negative throughout. Context-free analysis produces themes that misrepresent the actual experience trajectory.</reason>
      </antipattern>
      <rule>
        <statement>Always analyze at two levels: per-participant journey (individual arc) and cross-participant theme (aggregate pattern). Never report only aggregate themes without individual journey context.</statement>
        <rationale>Individual journey analysis catches the timing of experience change (when does positive turn negative). Aggregate analysis alone cannot reveal turning points.</rationale>
      </rule>
    </section>

    <section name="antipatterns-over-quantifying">
      <antipattern>
        <description>Reducing all diary data to counts and averages and reporting only quantitative metrics without representative quotes.</description>
        <reason>Diary studies produce rich qualitative data because participants self-report in their own language. Converting all of it to frequency counts discards the behavioral detail and contextual nuance that differentiates diary studies from surveys.</reason>
      </antipattern>
    </section>

    <section name="antipatterns-confirmation-bias">
      <antipattern>
        <description>Running the coding pass with the research hypothesis visible in the coding prompt, causing the coder to force entries into hypothesis-confirming categories.</description>
        <reason>LLM coding agents amplify confirmation bias when the prompt mentions a hypothesis upfront. The agent treats the hypothesis as a prior and interprets ambiguous entries as supporting it. This produces an inflated apparent confirmation rate.</reason>
      </antipattern>
      <rule>
        <statement>Run the entry coding pass blind to prior hypotheses. Strip all hypothesis text from the coder prompt. Expose hypotheses only to the final synthesizer, and require it to report entries that contradict each hypothesis explicitly.</statement>
        <rationale>Blind coding is the standard for inter-rater reliability. The synthesizer's job is to assess whether the coded evidence supports, contradicts, or is neutral to each hypothesis — not to confirm them.</rationale>
      </rule>
    </section>

    <section name="agentic-workflow">
      <p>Stand up a directory `study-data/` with one subfolder per participant containing one Markdown file per day plus an `entries.csv` index (`participant_id,date,prompt_id,text,media_path,sentiment`). Run a `coder` subagent over each entry to assign theme codes + sentiment + context tags into a JSON sidecar. A `synthesizer` subagent then reads all sidecars, computes per-theme frequency, per-day sentiment timeline, and generates the report from `templates.md`. Keep a human-in-loop checkpoint between coding and synthesis: human reviews the codebook before themes are locked.</p>
      <note>Recommended subagents: `diary-coder` (reads each entry, applies a fixed codebook, writes `&lt;entry&gt;.codes.json`, stateless parallel-safe haiku-class); `theme-synthesizer` (consumes all `.codes.json`, produces theme matrix + temporal chart data + quote bank, sonnet-class); `qa-monitor` (daily cron job: counts entries per participant, flags &lt;60% completion or text similarity &gt;0.9 across entries); `faion-sdd-executor-agent` (drives the report writeup as an SDD task).</note>
    </section>

    <section name="coding-pass-prompt-pattern">
      <p>Coding pass:</p>
      <code lang="text"><![CDATA[You are coding a single diary entry against a fixed codebook.
Codebook: <inline list of 6-12 themes with definitions>
Output strict JSON: {themes:[], sentiment:-1..1, context:"", quotes:[], severity:"low|med|high"}
Do not invent themes. If none fit, return themes=[].
Entry: <<<TEXT>>>]]></code>
      <p>Synthesis pass:</p>
      <code lang="text"><![CDATA[Inputs: all coded entries (JSONL).
Tasks:
1) Per-theme: frequency, participants-touched, top 3 quotes (with participant + day).
2) Per-day: average sentiment, dominant theme.
3) Outliers: entries flagged severity=high.
Output: fill the analysis template literally; cite participant+day for every quote.]]></code>
    </section>

    <section name="cli-tools">
      <p>Tools and services for diary study execution:</p>
      <list>
        <item>whisper (openai-whisper): Voice-entry transcription before coding. Install: `pip install openai-whisper`.</item>
        <item>ffmpeg: Voice/video normalization, silence trim. System package.</item>
        <item>exiftool: Strip GPS/EXIF from participant photos. apt / brew.</item>
        <item>csvkit (csvstat, csvcut): Quick frequency stats on entry index. Install: `pip install csvkit`.</item>
        <item>pandoc: Render report template to PDF/DOCX for stakeholders. System package.</item>
        <item>gh CLI: Track action items as issues from recommendations. Command: `gh issue create`.</item>
      </list>
    </section>

    <section name="saas-and-platforms">
      <p>Services and apps for diary study data collection and management:</p>
      <list>
        <item>dscout (SaaS): Partial agent integration via API for project and response export. Industry standard for diary studies; pull entries via API, code locally.</item>
        <item>Indeemo (SaaS): Partial agent integration; exports CSV/MP4. Mobile-first diary; agent consumes export, not live stream.</item>
        <item>User Interviews (SaaS): Recruitment only. Use for participant pool, not analysis.</item>
        <item>Dovetail (SaaS): Yes, REST API + tagging. Good store for coded entries; agent posts codes via API.</item>
        <item>Notion / Airtable (SaaS): Yes, official APIs. Lightweight DIY diary backend; agent reads + writes columns.</item>
        <item>EthOS by Dub (SaaS): Limited integration. Closed export, treat as data island.</item>
      </list>
    </section>

    <section name="best-practices">
      <list>
        <item>Lock the codebook before coding starts. Adding a theme mid-study invalidates earlier passes — re-run coder agent on full set.</item>
        <item>Force the coder to cite verbatim text fragments per theme; this lets the synthesizer pull real quotes without re-reading raw entries.</item>
        <item>Keep `participant_id` opaque (P01..P0N) in all agent contexts. Never feed real names to an LLM.</item>
        <item>Run two independent coder passes (different temperature seeds) on a 10% sample and compute Cohen's kappa. &lt;0.6 means codebook is ambiguous.</item>
        <item>Tag every entry with its prompt type (signal-contingent vs event-contingent vs end-of-day) — temporal patterns differ wildly.</item>
        <item>Store agent-generated themes/quotes in a write-once log; never let synthesizer overwrite earlier coding decisions.</item>
      </list>
    </section>

    <section name="ai-agent-gotchas">
      <list>
        <item>Diary entries are emotional, often venting. LLM safety filters may refuse to code entries about frustration, health, or family conflict. Pre-classify and route sensitive entries to a less-filtered local model or human.</item>
        <item>Memory bias: when the synthesizer sees themes from earlier participants, it tends to force later ones into the same buckets. Code each entry independently before synthesizing.</item>
        <item>"In-the-moment" claim is often false: participants reconstruct evenings. Agent should not treat timestamps as ground truth — use the entry's self-reported moment when available.</item>
        <item>Photo entries: EXIF leaks home address, work location, device serials. Strip before any vision-API call.</item>
        <item>Quote attribution must be exact verbatim. Agents paraphrase by default — explicitly require character-for-character quotes in the prompt and validate by substring match against source.</item>
        <item>Drop-off recovery: do NOT have the agent send the recovery DM. That conversation must be human; agent only flags the candidate.</item>
      </list>
    </section>

    <templates>
      <template path="templates/synthesis.md" purpose="Analysis output skeleton: participation summary, theme blocks with verbatim quotes, temporal patterns, recommendations."/>
      <template path="templates/qa-monitor.sh" purpose="Bash script flagging participants below 60% completion and suspected copy-paste entries."/>
    </templates>

